                <head>127. Memorandum From the Deputy Secretary of Defense (<persName
                        corresp="#p_NP1" type="from">Nitze</persName>) to the Chairman of the Joint
                    Chiefs of Staff (<persName corresp="#p_WGE1" type="to">Wheeler</persName>)<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d127fn1">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, Department of Defense, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss> Files:
                            <gloss target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 330 73 A 1304, 1968 Secretary of
                        Defense Files, VIET 370. Top Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-03-14">March 14, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Southeast Asia Deployments</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President would like us to meet General <persName corresp="#p_WGWC1"
                        >Westmoreland</persName>’s latest request for an additional 30,000 troops.
                    Therefore, I plan to issue a new Southeast Asia deployment plan, Program #6,
                    with a total military personnel strength of 565,500. This number includes the
                    525,000 in <pb facs="0426" n="382" xml:id="pg_382"/> Program #5, the 10,500
                    emergency reinforcement on loan to <gloss target="#t_MACV1">MACV</gloss>, and
                    the new request for 30,000. The Deputy Secretary of Defense will reply
                    separately to your request for cancellation of the civilianization program.</p>
                <p>I would like us to comply substantially with General <persName corresp="#p_WGWC1"
                        >Westmoreland</persName>’s preferred alternative. However, I would prefer to
                    substitute Army and Air Force units of similar types for the Marine Corps units
                    on his list. Because of the high fraction of the Marine Corps already deployed,
                    the Marines would find it very difficult, perhaps impossible, to sustain the
                    additional deployment under current personnel tour policies. Moreover,
                    substitution of Army and Air Force units would permit us to use the Marines in
                    missions closer to those for which they are designed.</p>
                <p>Therefore, I would like to propose the following approximation to General
                        <persName corresp="#p_WGWC1">Westmoreland</persName>’s preferred
                    alternative.</p>
